no-useless-coalescing

Flags redundant nullish coalescing (??) and logical OR (||) expressions
where the fallback can never be reached or doesn't change the result.

Source: https://github.com/oxc-project/tsgolint/issues/703
Implementation based on: https://github.com/oxc-project/tsgolint/pull/704

What Gets Flagged

1. Useless coalescing (dead fallback)

   The left side can never trigger the fallback, so the right side is dead code.

     const x: string = getString();
     x || '';           // error: string is always string, '' is identity
     x ?? 'fallback';   // error: string can never be nullish

     const obj: { name: string } = getObj();
     obj || undefined;  // error: object is always truthy

2. Redundant undefined fallback

   The expression already includes undefined in its type, so falling back
   to undefined is a no-op.

     declare const x: string | undefined;
     x ?? undefined;    // error: x is already T | undefined
     x || undefined;    // error: when x is undefined, || gives undefined anyway

     declare const arr: string[] | undefined;
     arr || undefined;  // error: same thing
     arr || void 0;     // error: void 0 is undefined too

3. Identity fallbacks

   The fallback is the same falsy value the type already produces.

     const s: string = getStr();
     s || '';            // error: when s is '', || gives '' anyway

     const b: boolean = getBool();
     b || false;         // error: when b is false, || gives false anyway

     const n: bigint = getBigInt();
     n || 0n;            // error: when n is 0n, || gives 0n anyway

What Is NOT Flagged

  - Expressions with any, unknown, or type parameters (can't reason statically)
  - x ?? null (different from undefined)
  - x || 'default' where x could be nullish (the fallback changes behavior)
  - x || undefined where x includes null (|| normalizes null to undefined)

Auto-fix

All diagnostics include an auto-fix that removes the operator and fallback
expression, leaving just the left side.
